{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a96340fb-d165-4b74-89b5-f8aec5b07578","content":"Here's how to migrate your xUnit.net test project to Microsoft.Testing.Platform:\n\n**1. Update package references** in your `.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<!-- Remove -->\n<PackageReference Include=\"xunit.runner.visualstudio\" Version=\"...\" />\n\n<!-- Add -->\n<PackageReference Include=\"xunit.runner.mtp\" Version=\"1.0.0\" />\n```\n\nKeep your existing `xunit` 2.9.3 package as-is.\n\n**2. Enable MTP** in your `.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <TestingPlatformDotNetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotNetTestSupport>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n**3. Run tests** with:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test\n```\n\nOr run the test project directly as an executable (MTP makes test projects self-contained apps):\n\n```bash\ndotnet run --project YourTests.csproj -- --help\n```\n\n**Key notes:**\n- `xunit.runner.mtp` replaces `xunit.runner.visualstudio` — they shouldn't coexist.\n- No test code changes are needed; your `[Fact]`/`[Theory]` tests work as before.\n- If you use `dotnet test`, the `TestingPlatformDotNetTestSupport` property bridges `dotnet test` to MTP.\n- Check the [xUnit MTP docs](https://xunit.net/docs/getting-started/microsoft-testing-platform) for advanced runner options.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"40e62bcf-cad8-46fa-ba20-f6a19ea845df","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to migrate their xUnit.net project from VSTest (using xunit.runner.visualstudio) to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP). Let me provide a concise answer based on my knowledge of this migration path.","outputTokens":433,"requestId":"CFC9:1FFE72:629B501:6DC69DB:69EC0E80"},"id":"9889d640-246f-49fe-b9d9-9edb8ef4aa8e","timestamp":"2026-04-25T00:44:58.026Z","parentId":"44602b94-daee-4327-8ccb-01a0adca76b2"}
